<h2>
    Introduction: Medford’s Gateway to Southern Oregon Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    Located in the heart of the Rogue Valley, <strong>Medford, Oregon</strong> is a paradise for anglers. With its mild climate, diverse landscapes, and easy access to mountain lakes and famous rivers, Medford offers fishing opportunities year-round. Whether you're chasing wild steelhead in the Rogue River or trolling for kokanee in Applegate Lake, this region has something for everyone—from seasoned fly fishers to weekend bank anglers.
</p>
<h2>
    Fish Species You Can Catch Near Medford
</h2>
<p>
    Southern Oregon waters are rich in variety. Here's what you can expect to catch:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rainbow Trout &amp; Cutthroat Trout</strong> – Found in nearly all lakes and rivers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Steelhead</strong> – Winter and summer runs in the Rogue and Applegate Rivers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Chinook &amp; Coho Salmon</strong> – Seasonal runs in the Rogue River.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Largemouth &amp; Smallmouth Bass</strong> – Popular in warmwater lakes.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Kokanee Salmon</strong> – Found in deeper reservoirs like Applegate and Lost Creek.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Catfish, Bluegill &amp; Crappie</strong> – Common in Emigrant and Agate Lakes.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Prime Fishing Lakes Near Medford, Oregon
</h2>
<h3>
    Applegate Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Located 45 minutes southwest of Medford, Applegate Lake is known for <strong>kokanee, rainbow trout, and smallmouth bass</strong>. Fish near the dam for kokanee or troll deeper sections during summer.
</p>
<h3>
    Emigrant Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Just outside of town, Emigrant is stocked with <strong>trout</strong> in spring and fall. It also supports <strong>bass, catfish, and panfish</strong>. Great for families and kayak anglers.
</p>
<h3>
    Lost Creek Lake
</h3>
<p>
    A large reservoir northeast of Medford with great facilities and consistent trout fishing. Trolling and bank fishing are popular methods here. Holds <strong>chinook, rainbow trout, and even some landlocked steelhead</strong>.
</p>
<h3>
    Howard Prairie &amp; Hyatt Lake
</h3>
<p>
    High-elevation lakes east of Ashland with excellent spring and early summer trout fishing. Cooler temps and scenic views make them great camping and fishing destinations.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Rivers for Fishing Near Medford
</h2>
<h3>
    Rogue River
</h3>
<p>
    A <strong>world-class steelhead and salmon fishery</strong>, the Rogue runs from Crater Lake to the Pacific Ocean. Near Medford, it offers <strong>summer and winter steelhead</strong>, <strong>spring and fall Chinook</strong>, and <strong>resident trout</strong>. Use spinners, drift gear, or flies depending on the season.
</p>
<h3>
    Applegate River
</h3>
<p>
    Smaller and more intimate than the Rogue, the Applegate is a popular winter steelhead destination. Fly anglers enjoy solitude and challenge here. Only open to catch-and-release trout fishing in summer months.
</p>
<h3>
    Bear Creek
</h3>
<p>
    An <strong>urban stream</strong> flowing right through Medford. While smaller and more sensitive, it can hold seasonal steelhead and trout in cooler months. Best fished after rainfall when water levels rise.
</p>
