<h2>
    Frequently Asked Questions About Fishing Near Medford, Oregon
</h2>
<p>
    <strong>Q1: What’s the best lake near Medford for trout?</strong><br>
    <strong>Applegate Lake</strong> and <strong>Lost Creek Lake</strong> are both excellent for stocked and holdover trout.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q2: When is steelhead season in the Rogue River?</strong><br>
    <strong>Summer steelhead</strong> run from July–October; <strong>winter steelhead</strong> peak from January–March.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q3: Can I fish in Medford city limits?</strong><br>
    Yes—<strong>Bear Creek</strong> and <strong>Emigrant Lake</strong> are very close to town.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q4: Do I need a boat to fish lakes near Medford?</strong><br>
    No—but a kayak or boat helps on larger reservoirs like Lost Creek. Bank fishing is effective too.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q5: Are there bass near Medford?</strong><br>
    Yes—<strong>Emigrant Lake</strong>, <strong>Agate Lake</strong>, and <strong>Applegate Lake</strong> all hold largemouth and smallmouth bass.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q6: What’s the best fly fishing river near Medford?</strong><br>
    The <strong>Rogue River</strong> offers the best variety and challenge for fly anglers.
</p>
